# Frontend UX and motion rules

Apply these rules when editing UI, styling, state flow, or interaction behavior.

## Mobile-first UI
- Start with phone portrait layout
- Prefer stacked card layouts over dense tables
- Use large tap targets
- Keep primary actions easy to reach with one hand
- Use sticky score summary or sticky action bars when it improves round entry
- Avoid layout jumps during input

## Motion and feedback
This product should feel alive during play.

Use animation for:
- entry transitions
- drag-and-drop feedback
- Tichu selection feedback
- save success feedback
- score update feedback
- round history insertion / removal
- error feedback
- end-game winner state
- dark mode transitions

## Motion quality bar
- Motion must clarify state changes
- Keep transitions quick and responsive
- Avoid heavy animation dependencies unless truly necessary
- Preserve performance on mobile devices
- Always provide reduced-motion fallback

## UI decision heuristic
When there is a tradeoff, prefer:
1. input speed
2. readability on small screens
3. clear score visibility
4. maintainable implementation
5. visual flourish
